{"type":"message","id":"326ae227","parentId":"ee116624","timestamp":"2026-03-03T16:29:28.453Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"**Considering Scheduling Options**\n\nI'm currently evaluating the best approach for the recurring reminder. My initial thought is that `cron` appears promising for scheduling the daily weekday task at 9 am ET and using Telegram to send a message. I'm focusing on how `cron.add` can facilitate this recurring schedule.\n\n\n**Refining Cron Configuration**\n\nI'm now zeroing in on the specifics of the `cron.add` configuration. The naming convention will be \"Daily Task Review Reminder.\" The cron expression will be `0 9 * * 1-5`, with \"America/New_York\" as the timezone. The payload will be a `systemEvent` within the main session, conveying the Telegram message: \"Reminder: Time to review your tasks.\" The delivery will use \"announce\" mode and specify \"telegram\" as the channel.\n\n\n**Delegating Task Creation**\n\nI've realized that creating the daily reminder involves \"external-delivery\" (Telegram messaging), aligning with ORION's delegation policy. I am now preparing a Task Packet for ATLAS, detailing the \"Daily Task Review Reminder\" job, its schedule (0 9 * * 1-5), the \"America/New_York\" timezone, and the Telegram message: \"Reminder: Time to review your tasks.\" The task packet will specify an `announce` delivery using the \"telegram\" channel and target the \"main\" session. This shift ensures compliance with the established workflow.\n\n\n**Orchestrating Task Delegation**\n\nI've determined that due to the \"external-delivery\" aspect (Telegram messaging) and the established ORION guidelines for `cron` tasks, delegating the reminder setup to ATLAS is the appropriate course of action. I am now formulating a Task Packet to provide ATLAS with the necessary details to create the \"Daily Task Review Reminder\".\n\n\n**Refining Delegation Parameters**\n\nI'm now detailing the `Task Packet` for ATLAS, incorporating all known factors. This will include the job's complete specifications: the name \"Daily Task Review Reminder,\" the schedule (0 9 * * 1-5, America/New_York), the `systemEvent` payload with the Telegram message (\"Reminder: Time to review your tasks.\"), and the delivery (`announce` with the `telegram` channel). This ensures ATLAS has all details to create and manage the requested recurring reminder efficiently and in compliance.\n\n\n**Orchestrating Task Delegation**\n\nI'm finalizing the delegation process. My current approach involves generating a `Task Packet` for ATLAS, as direct configuration would violate ORION's established guidelines. The `Task Packet` will provide comprehensive details for creating the recurring reminder job, including its name, schedule, payload (Telegram message), and delivery method. This delegation ensures a compliant and efficient task management workflow.\n\n\n**Orchestrating Task Delegation**\n\nI've crafted a Task Packet intended for ATLAS, aligning with ORION's established practices for managing cron tasks involving external services like Telegram. The packet details the \"Daily Task Review Reminder\" job, its specific schedule, message content, and delivery mechanism, ensuring seamless orchestration of the required recurring reminder. I am now finalizing its transmission.\n\n\n**Orchestrating Task Delegation**\n\nI've carefully considered the nature of this task and am now constructing the appropriate `TASK_PACKET` for ATLAS. I've considered all factors from the original request, and I've ensured compliance with the workflow restrictions. I'm preparing the full details for the daily reminder job.\n\n\n\n"},{"type":"text","text":"<think>The user is asking to set a recurring reminder that includes sending a message on Telegram. According to the AGENTS.md, cron/scheduling/reminder requests that involve multi-step, risky, or external-delivery workflows should be delegated to ATLAS. This request involves schedulin